2. Implement the export functions: Implement the export functions for each format using PHP libraries or external APIs. For example, you can use the PHPWord library to export the report to a Microsoft Word document, or the PHPExcel library to export the report to a Microsoft Excel spreadsheet.
3. Add export options to the user interface: Add export options to the user interface, such as a drop-down menu or a set of radio buttons, to allow the user to choose the desired export format.
4. Generate the export: Generate the export in the chosen format by using the appropriate PHP library or external API. Here is an example of exporting a report to a PDF using the TCPDF library:
```php
require_once('tcpdf/tcpdf.php');

$pdf = new TCPDF(PDF_PAGE_ORIENTATION, PDF_UNIT, PDF_PAGE_FORMAT, true, 'UTF-8', false);

$pdf->AddPage();
$pdf->writeHTML($report, true, false, true, false, '');
$pdf->Output('appraisal_report.pdf', 'D');
```
5. Test the exports: Test the exports by generating sample reports and exporting them in different formats. If the exports are generated correctly, the export options are working as expected.

By following these steps, you can implement export options for exporting the final appraisal report in a variety of formats in your web-based commercial appraisal report writing application. If you need further assistance, please let me know.

Yes, it is possible to create reports using Apex in Salesforce. You can use the Apex programming language to query data from Salesforce objects and then generate reports based on that data.

Here are the general steps you can follow to create a report using Apex:

1. Query the data that you want to include in the report using SOQL (Salesforce Object Query Language). You can use SOQL to retrieve data from any Salesforce object or related object.
2. Create a new instance of the `Report` class and populate its properties with the appropriate values. The `Report` class represents a report definition in Salesforce.
3. Create a new instance of the `ReportMetadata` class and populate its properties with the appropriate values. The `ReportMetadata` class contains metadata about the report, such as its name, description, and columns.
4. Use the `ReportingService` class to generate the report based on the `Report` and `ReportMetadata` objects. The `ReportingService` class provides methods for generating, previewing, and updating reports.
5. Save the report to Salesforce using the `Reports` object.

Here's an example of how to create a report using Apex:
```java
// Query data using SOQL
List<Account> accounts = [SELECT Id, Name, AnnualRevenue FROM Account WHERE Industry = 'Technology'];

// Create a new report
Report report = new Report();
report.DeveloperName = 'My_Report';
report.Name = 'My Report';
report.Format = 'Tabular';

// Create report metadata
ReportMetadata metadata = new ReportMetadata();
metadata.columns = new List<String>{'Name', 'AnnualRevenue'};
metadata.description = 'My custom report';
metadata.name = 'My Report';
metadata.reportType = 'Account';

// Generate the report
ReportingService service = new ReportingService();
List<ReportResult> results = service.runReport(report, metadata, accounts);

// Save the report to Salesforce
Reports reportObject = new Reports();
reportObject.Name = 'My Report';
reportObject.DeveloperName = 'My_Report';
reportObject.NamespacePrefix = 'my_namespace';
reportObject.FolderName = 'Unfiled Public Reports';
reportObject.DeveloperName = 'My_Report';
reportObject.IsActive = true;
reportObject.LastReferencedDate = System.now();
reportObject.LastViewedDate = System.now();
reportObject.ContentType = 'Tabular';
reportObject.Description = 'My custom report';
reportObject.Format = 'Tabular';
reportObject.HasDetailRows = false;
reportObject.HasRecordCount = true;
reportObject.ReportType = 'Account';
reportObject.Query = results[0].query;

insert reportObject;
```
This example generates a tabular report that displays the name and annual revenue of all accounts in the Technology industry. You can customize this code to generate different types of reports based on your business needs.

You are to write a on road scenario configuration in pbtxt format (with other road agents like vehicles and pedestrians) that can be loaded into a self driving car simulation system to check if ego vehicle (called nurobot) can make correct decisions. The configuration contains other road agents, their behaviors, and conditions to check if the ego vehicle's behavior is expected. 
Here are some general instructions
- Check the final configuration against the protobuf definition to make sure it is syntax correct
- Ego vehicle is a planner agent
- Other road agents are line follower agents
- Make sure the geo locations are accurate up to 8 digits after decimal

Below are relevant protobuf definitions: 

// A 3D (lat, lng, alt) coordinate on Earth expressed in the WGS84 standard.
message GeographicPointProto {
 double lat = 1;
 double lng = 2;
 double alt = 3;
}
message PlannerAgentConfig {
 repeated GeographicPointProto route\_points = 1;

 double start\_yaw = 2;
 // Application order: tangent, norm, yaw
 Expression fuzz\_tangent = 3;
 Expression fuzz\_norm = 4;
 Expression fuzz\_yaw = 5;

 // Range of detection. 0/unset for unlimited range.
 double detection\_range = 6;

 // Path to simulator config used for this planner agent.
 // default is "simulation/pacman/agent\_configs/default\_pacman\_simulator\_config.pbtxt"
 string simulator\_config = 7;

 // Max number of seconds the agent should live for.
 double max\_duration = 8;

 // Max number of warmup seconds the agent should live for.
 Expression warm\_up\_duration\_expr = 26;

 // Runtime check
 repeated Expression runtime\_check = 12;

 Expression initial\_speed = 13;
}
message SceneConfig {
 // location of the ego vehicle
 GeographicPointProto localization\_point = 1;

 // agent name to configuration mapping
 map agent\_configs = 2;

 // actions triggered by simulation in the scene, including agent creation
 repeated Expression actions = 3;

 // Mapping from groups to expressions, where expression returns an array of
 // fuzzed variances to run for this group.
 map fuzzing\_specs = 4;
}

message LineFollowingAgentConfig {
 repeated GeographicPointProto route\_points = 1;

 // The velocity the vehicle would drive at in free traffic
 Expression desired\_speed = 2;
 Expression max\_accel = 3;
 Expression comfort\_braking = 4;
 // The minimum possible time to the vehicle in front
 Expression desired\_time\_headway = 5;
 // Initial speed.
 Expression initial\_speed = 6;
 // Max acceleration on norm/lat direction.
 Expression max\_acc\_norm = 7;
 // Max curvature of the trajectory.
 Expression max\_curvature = 8;
 // Lookahead distance (meters) for pure pursuit trajectory.
 Expression lookahead\_distance = 9;

 oneof model\_info\_oneof {
 ModelType model\_type = 10;
 ModelConfig model\_config = 11;
 }

 // The max braking hard limit acc. If not provided, default to 8m/s^2
 // Needs a positive number.
 Expression max\_braking = 12;

 // Runtime check
 repeated Expression runtime\_check = 13;
}
enum Engine {
 UNSPECIFIED = 0;
 PLANNER = 1;
 LINE\_FOLLOWING = 2;
}

message AgentConfig {
 Engine engine = 4;
 // Agent specific configs.
 oneof agent\_config\_oneof {
 PlannerAgentConfig planner = 1;
 LineFollowingAgentConfig line\_following = 2;
 }
}
message LambdaFuncProto {
 repeated string args = 1;
 Expression expr = 2;
}

message ObjectValueProto {
 map fields = 1;
}

message ArrayProto {
 repeated SymbolValueProto values = 1;
}

message Vector2Proto {
 double x = 1;
 double y = 2;
}

message Polygon2Proto {
 repeated Vector2Proto points = 1;
}

// Next ID: 11
message SymbolValueProto {
 enum ValueType {
 UNDEFINED = 0;
 BOOLEAN = 1;
 DOUBLE = 2;
 STRING = 3;
 POLYGON = 4;
 VECTOR2 = 5;
 FUNCTION = 6;
 LAMBDA = 7;
 ACTION = 8;
 ARRAY = 9;
 ERROR = 10;
 OBJECT = 12;

 // For Type reference use only.
 ANY = 11;
 }
 oneof symbol\_value\_oneof {
 bool v\_bool = 1;
 double v\_double = 2;
 string v\_string = 3;
 Polygon2Proto v\_poly2 = 4;
 Vector2Proto v\_vector2 = 5;
 ActionProto v\_action = 6;
 LambdaFuncProto v\_lambda = 7;
 ObjectValueProto v\_object = 8;
 ArrayProto v\_array = 9;
 }
}

message IfExpression {
 Expression condition = 1;
 Expression true\_value = 2;
 Expression false\_value = 3;
}

// Next ID: 9
message Expression {
 oneof expression\_oneof {
 SymbolValueProto constant = 6;
 string var = 4;
 FuncCall expr = 5;
 IfExpression if\_exp = 8;
 string raw\_expr = 9;
 Property property = 10;
 }
 reserved 1 to 3;

 message FuncCall {
 enum Operator {
 CUSTOM = 0;

 // Arithmetic
 SUM = 1;
 MINUS = 2;
 MULTIPLE = 3;
 DIV = 4;

 // Comparison
 LE = 5;
 LT = 6;
 GE = 7;
 GT = 8;
 EQ = 9;
 NE = 10;

 // Logical
 AND = 11;
 OR = 12;
 NOT = 13;

 // Other
 MAKE\_ARRAY = 14;

 NEG = 15;
 }
 Operator op = 1;

 repeated Expression values = 2;
 // If op is CUSTOM, it will invoke the evaluated function.
 Expression callee = 3;
 }
 message Property {
 Expression base = 1;
 string identifier = 2;
 }
}

message ActionProto {
 string action\_type = 1;

 repeated SymbolValueProto info = 2;
}

message Type {
 message ArgDescription {
 Type type = 1;
 string name = 2;
 string description = 3;
 }
 message FunctionType {
 repeated ArgDescription args = 1;
 // If exist, this is the last argument and can accept any number of
 // params.
 ArgDescription varargs = 2;

 ArgDescription return\_value = 3;
 }
 message ArrayType {
 Type element\_type = 1;
 }
 // Could be any of [potential\_types].
 message UnionType {
 repeated Type potential\_types = 1;
 }

 oneof type {
 SymbolValueProto.ValueType primitive\_type = 1;
 FunctionType func = 2;
 ArrayType array = 3;
 UnionType union\_type = 4;
 }
}

